narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Informed by the thoughts of scholars Tina Campt, Fred Moten, douard Glissant, and visiting professors alike, the class has offered a multidimensional glimpse into the socioeconomic intricacies of the physical and intangible world across scales of time and place. Specific topics of discussion have included air rights and their associated injustices, slave marronage, indigenous conceptions of land use, depictions of Blackness through various mediums, and much more.
I learned about the interdisciplinary nature of the field of architecture and the relationship between the ground/verticality/zoning and social issues, especially those pertaining to race.
Critical analysis of theory and difficult texts to understand a dealer meaning.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Professor Vanable, along with the TA and Pedagogical Partner, readily changed methods of engaging all classroom members to ensure all participated.
This course was the best course I have taken at Yale so far. Ife is a great professor and inspiring thinker, who facilitated excellent and engaging class discussions.
Great discussion that forced students to think deeper about texts.
Ife is fantastic. This course opened my eyes to a new way of thinking. The course material was phenomenal.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, this class offers a view of nonconformist scholarly thought and culminates in a written work that truly captures the breadth of all topics studied in class.

I would recommend this course to anyone who is looking for a though-provoking writing credit. It also had a very interesting and diverse group of students (not everyone was an architecture major), which made class discussions really generative.
Yes. It was unlike any other class Ive taken and really interesting

TAKE THIS CLASS! Ife is a gem at the School of Architecture. Every class was engaging, and she really cared about the work of her students. She is a challenging professor, but she wants her students to do well, all you need to do is engage and put in the work. I would take this class all over again if I could.
